Chap. 1 - Data Visualization with ggplot2

First Steps

Question to Answer - do cars with big engines use more fuel than cars with small engines?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

The mapping argument is always paired with aes(), and the args for aes specify the x and y values.

  1. What does the drv variable describe? The type of drivetrain - front, rear, 4wd
# ?mpg
  1. Make a scatterplot of hwy vs cyl
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cyl))

  1. What happens if you make a scatterplot of class vs drv? Why is the plot not useful? Answer Because this creates a scatterplot from 2 categorical variables.
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = class, y = drv))

Aesthetic Mappings

An aesthetic is a visual property of the objects in your plot. Things like size, shape, or the color of your points.

This plot maps the colors of the points in the class variable to reveal the class of each car.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class))

This plot maps the size discrete variable to the class (not recommended).

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

Here, we map class to the alpha aesthetic, which controls the transparency of the points, or their shape.

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, alpha = class))
## Warning: Using alpha for a discrete variable is not advised.

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class))
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values
## because more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 7.
## Consider specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 62 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Exercise 1.2

  1. What is wrong with the code below? Answer A parenthese should be after hwy and removed from the end. Color goes outside of aes!!
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = "blue"))

  1. Map a continuous variable to color, size, & shape. How are these different for categorical vs continuous variables? Answer For continuous variables, there is one color with different shades of the same color. For categorical variables, there are different colors for each categorical variable.
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = displ, color = cty))

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = displ, color = fl))

  1. What happens if you map the same variable to multiple aesthetics? Answer Plot works, but does not provide any additional information.
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = displ, color = hwy))

  1. What does the stroke aesthetic do? What shapes does it work with? Answer Modifies the width of the border of shapes.
ggplot(data = mpg, aes(hwy, displ)) + 
  geom_point(shape = 21, colour = "black", fill = "yellow", size = 5, stroke = 2)

  1. What happens if you map an aesthetic to something other than a variable name like ase(color = displ < 5)? Answer Cool! Shows values less than 5 in one color, >= 5 in another!
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = displ, color = displ < 5))
